          "text": "Work on Linear issue MAGE-613:\n\n<issue identifier=\"MAGE-613\">\n<title>iOS: JWT parsing and validation</title>\n<description>\n## Summary\n\nImplement JWT parsing and validation for the iOS SDK. This is the foundational layer that the auth token manager will use to decide whether a returned token is usable and when it should be refreshed.\n\n## Scope\n\n* Pure-Swift JWT parser that extracts the `exp` and `iat` claims (RFC 7519 NumericDate). No other claims are read; `sub`, audience, issuer, and custom claims are opaque to the SDK.\n* `ValidatedToken` struct (or equivalent) holding the raw JWT string alongside its decoded `exp` and `iat` as `Date` values.\n* Validation rules — reject tokens that:\n  * Fail to decode (malformed Base64URL, malformed JSON, missing claims).\n  * Are already expired at the time of acquisition, applying a 15-second clock-skew leeway (`now >= exp - leeway` means expired).\n* No signature verification. The SDK is not a security boundary; the Klaviyo backend performs full validation.\n* `OSLog`-based logging of validation failures with the reason (missing claim / malformed / expired on receipt). Token contents NEVER logged; use `.private` privacy markers on token-adjacent values.\n\n## Notes\n\nThis work has no runtime dependencies on the rest of the auth token system and is easy to unit-test in isolation. The downstream `AuthTokenManager` ticket consumes the `ValidatedToken` type to schedule refreshes and detect expiry.\n\n## References\n\n* [Spec: Personalized In-App Forms — Auth Token Integration](<https://linear.app/klaviyo/document/personalized-in-app-forms-auth-token-integration-03d3495f6093>) — §JWT contract, §Clock skew tolerance, §Logging and observability\n</description>\n<team name=\"Mobile App Growth\"/>\n<project name=\"JWT support in SDK/onsite\">Implement authenticated client APIs to securely transmit PII to end-user devices. This enables personalized content for in-app and onsite forms, which is essential