        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "**What Base64 even is:** a way to write any blob of bytes using only printable letters and digits. Binary data has weird unprintable bytes; Base64 squeezes 3 bytes into 4 characters from a 64-letter alphabet: `A-Z`, `a-z`, `0-9`, plus two extras: `+` and `/`. So \"Base 64.\"\n\n**Why \"URL\"-safe Base64:** `+` and `/` mean special things in URLs (`+` becomes a space, `/` is a path separator). If you stuff a regular Base64 string into a URL or a JWT, it gets mangled. So the JWT spec said: swap `+` → `-` and `/` → `_`. Same idea, two safer characters.\n\n**Why `=` padding:** Base64 works in groups of 4 characters. If your original data doesn't divide evenly, the encoder adds `=` signs at the end to round out the last group. JWT strips those off because the URL doesn't need them — you can always figure out how many were dropped from the length.\n\n**What our function does, step by step:**\n\n```swift\n.replacingOccurrences(of: \"-\", with: \"+\")\n.replacingOccurrences(of: \"_\", with: \"/\")\n```\nUndo the URL-safe swap, so the string looks like normal Base64 again.\n\n```swift\nlet paddingNeeded = (4 - normalized.count % 4) % 4\nnormalized.append(String(repeating: \"=\", count: paddingNeeded))\n```\nPut the missing `=` signs back. The math is a small trick:\n- `count % 4` is how many extra characters past a multiple of 4 we have (0, 1, 2, or 3).\n- `4 - that` is how many we need to round up... except when it's already a multiple of 4, that gives `4`, and we want `0`.\n- The outer `% 4` collapses that `4` back to `0`.\n\nSo: lengths ending in 0/1/2/3 extras → add 0/3/2/1 `=` signs.\n\n```swift\nreturn Data(base64Encoded: normalized)\n```\nHand the now-vanilla Base64 string to Foundation, which decodes it into raw bytes — that's the JSON payload of the JWT. Returns `nil` if the string still isn't valid Base64 (bad characters etc.), which our parser maps to `.malformedBase64`.\n\n**TL;DR:** JWTs use a slightly modified Base64 to survive URLs. This function un-modifies it (swap two characters, glue padding back on), then asks Foundation to do the actual decoding.",
