          "text": "Base directory for this skill: /Users/andrew.balmer/.claude/plugins/cache/klaviyo-plugins/mage/2.6.3/skills/clean-commit-history\n\n# Clean Commit History\n\nThis skill restructures a git branch's commit history so that each commit is a small,\nself-contained, logically coherent change. The goal is that a reviewer can walk through the\nPR commit-by-commit and understand the full story of the change without encountering WIP\nsnapshots, abandoned approaches, or bug-then-fix sequences.\n\n## Core Principles\n\nThese principles guide every decision about how to split, combine, and order commits:\n\n1. **Each commit tells one part of the story.** A commit should introduce one logical concept,\n   one piece of functionality, or one coherent refactor. A reviewer reading just that commit's\n   diff should understand what changed and why.\n\n2. **Small is better than large.** When in doubt, prefer smaller commits. A commit that touches\n   3 files for one reason is easier to review than one that touches 15 files for four reasons.\n\n3. **The final approach is the only approach.** If the engineer tried approach A, abandoned it,\n   and went with approach B, the history should only show approach B. Abandoned work, reverted\n   experiments, and dead ends are removed entirely.\n\n4. **Bugs were never introduced.** If a commit introduced a bug and a later commit fixed it,\n   fold the fix into the original commit so the bug never existed in the history.\n\n5. **WIP commits don't exist.** Any commit with a message like \"WIP\", \"wip\", \"save progress\",\n   \"tmp\", \"checkpoint\", etc. is dissolved — its changes are redistributed into logical commits.\n\n6. **Compilability is a goal, not a hard rule.** Ideally the code compiles at every commit. When\n   that isn't possible (because a later commit implements something this commit depends on), add\n   a `// TODO: Implement X in next commit` placeholder so the intent is clear.\n\n7. **No code changes beyond placeholders.** This skill never modifies the final state of the code.\n   The only code it may add is `// TODO: ...` comments on intermediate commits, and those TODOs\n   must be resolved by a later commit in the same PR. The final commit's tree must be identical\n   to the original branch tip.\n\n## Workflow\n\n### Step 1: Gather Context\n\nUnderstanding *what the branch is trying to accomplish* is essential for organizing commits\ninto a coherent narrative. Without this context, you're just grouping files — with it, you can\ntell a story.\n\n**Try these sources in order:**\n\n1. **Branch name** — Check if it contains a Linear ticket ID (e.g., `andrew/eng-123-feature-name`\n   or `eng-123/add-widget`). Common patterns: `<prefix>/<ticket-id>-<slug>` or\n   `<ticket-id>/<slug>`. Extract the ticket identifier.\n\n2. **Linear ticket** — If you found a ticket ID, look it up using `mcp__linear-server__get_issue`\n   (or search via `mcp__linear-server__list_issues` with the ticket ID as a query). Read the ticket\n   title, description, and any sub-issues to understand the scope and intent. This is the best\n   source of context.\n\n3. **Diff analysis** — If no Linear ticket is available, analyze the full diff between the branch\n   and its base. Look at file paths, function names, imports, test names, and comments to infer\n   what the branch is doing.\n\n4. **Ask the user** — If the above don't give you enough context, ask the user to briefly describe\n   what the branch is doing. Keep it lightweight: \"Can you give me a one-liner on what this\n   branch is for?\"\n\n### Step 2: Identify the Base Branch\n\nDetermine where this branch diverged from the main line:\n\n```bash\n# Try common base branch names, collect candidates\ncandidates=()\nfor base in main master develop; do\n  if git rev-parse --verify \"$base\" >/dev/null 2>&1; then\n    candidates+=(\"$base\")\n  fi\ndone\n```\n\n**When to confirm vs. proceed silently:**\n- **One candidate found** — use it and proceed without asking. Mention it in your output\n  (e.g., \"Using `main` as base branch\") so the user sees it but doesn't have to respond.\n- **Multiple candidates** — ask the user which branch this PR targets.\n- **No candidates** — ask the user to specify the base branch.\n\n### Step 3: Determine the Mode\n\nCheck the current state of the branch:\n\n```bash\n# Check for uncommitted changes\ngit status --porcelain\n\n# Check for commits ahead of the base branch\ngit log --oneline $(git merge-base <base> HEAD)..HEAD\n```\n\nThis determines which mode to operate in:\n\n- **Mode A (uncommitted changes):** There are unstaged/staged changes to organize into commits.\n- **Mode B (rewrite history):** The branch already has commits that need restructuring.\n- **Both:** There are existing commits AND uncommitted changes. Stage and commit everything\n  as a temporary commit first (`git add -A && git commit -m \"temp: stage uncommitted changes\"`),\n  then proceed with Mode B.\n\n### Step 4: Analyze the Changes\n\n#### For Mode A (uncommitted changes):\n\n```bash\n# See the full diff\ngit diff HEAD\ngit diff --cached  # staged changes too\n\n# List changed files\ngit diff HEAD --name-status\n```\n\nGroup the changes by logical theme. Look for natural boundaries:\n- Files that serve the same feature or module\n- Test files and the code they test\n- Configuration or build file changes\n- Documentation changes\n- Refactors that enable a feature vs. the feature itself\n\n#### For Mode B (rewrite history):\n\n```bash\n# See all commits on this branch\ngit log --oneline <merge-base>..HEAD\n\n# See the full diff of the entire branch (this is the \"truth\" — the final state)\ngit diff <merge-base>..HEAD\n\n# See each commit's diff individually\ngit log -p <merge-base>..HEAD\n```\n\nWhen analyzing existing commits, look for:\n- **WIP commits** — messages containing \"wip\", \"WIP\", \"work in progress\", \"save\", \"tmp\",\n  \"checkpoint\", \"fixup\", \"squash\", \"progress\", \"draft\"\n- **Bug-fix pairs** — a commit that introduces something broken, followed by a fix commit\n- **Abandoned approaches** — changes in early commits that are fully reverted or replaced later\n- **Scattered changes** — the same logical change spread across multiple commits\n- **Oversized commits** — commits that contain multiple unrelated changes\n\nThe key insight: **ignore the existing commit boundaries entirely.** Look only at the total\ndiff (`git diff <merge-base>..HEAD`) and plan the new history from scratch based on the final\nstate of the code.\n\n### Step 5: Plan the Commit Structure\n\nBased on your analysis, create an ordered list of commits. Each entry should have:\n- A conventional commit message (subject line, and body if it adds value)\n- A list of the files/changes included\n- A brief rationale for why this is its own commit\n\n**Commit message conventions:** Use [Conventional Commits v1.0.0](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/).\nIf the target repo's `CLAUDE.md` or `AGENTS.md` defines its own convention, that takes precedence.\n\n**Ordering principles:**\n- Infrastructure/config changes first (build files, dependencies, project config)\n- Refactors that enable a feature before the feature itself\n- Core logic before tests (unless TDD-style makes more sense for the story)\n- Each commit should build on the previous one — a reviewer going in order should never be\n  confused about why something exists\n\n**Deciding when to show the plan vs. execute autonomously:**\n\n- **5 or fewer commits with a straightforward structure** -> Execute autonomously. Briefly\n  summarize what you did after.\n- **6+ commits, or a complex restructuring** -> Present the plan to the user first and wait\n  for approval. Format it as a numbered list with commit messages and brief descriptions of\n  what each commit contains.\n\n**When rewriting existing history (Mode B), always show a before/after comparison** regardless\nof size. Show the old commit list alongside the proposed new commit list so the user can\nconfirm the restructuring makes sense.\n\n### Step 6: Execute the Plan\n\n#### Mode A: Committing Uncommitted Changes\n\n**First, snapshot the target state** so you can verify nothing is lost:\n```bash\n# Create a tree object from the current working tree (staged + unstaged)\ngit add -A\noriginal_tree=$(git write-tree)\ngit reset HEAD  # unstage everything again\n```\n\nFor each planned commit, stage the relevant files and commit:\n\n```bash\n# Stage specific files\ngit add <file1> <file2> ...\n\n# For partial file staging (when only some changes in a file belong to this commit)\n# Use git add -p or create a patch\ngit add -p <file>\n\n# Commit with the planned message\ngit commit -m \"type(scope): subject line\" -m \"Optional body explaining the why.\"\n```\n\n**Partial file staging** is important — sometimes a file contains changes for two different\nlogical commits. Use `git add -p` or manual patch application to split them correctly.\n\nIf a commit needs a TODO placeholder for compilability:\n\n1. Add the placeholder comment to the relevant file(s)\n2. Stage and commit with the placeholder included\n3. In the commit that implements the real code, the placeholder is naturally replaced\n\nAfter all commits are created, verify the final state matches:\n```bash\n# Compare the final committed tree against the snapshot taken earlier\ngit diff-tree --no-commit-id -r $original_tree HEAD\n# This MUST produce no output. If it does, something was lost or changed.\n```\n\n#### Mode B: Rewriting History\n\n**Save the original branch tip** so it can be recovered if anything goes wrong:\n```bash\n# Record the original HEAD — always needed for verification\nfinal_tree=$(git rev-parse HEAD)\n\n# If backup was passed in , create a named backup branch\ngit branch backup/<branch-name>-pre-cleanup  # only if backup\n```\n\nThe approach is to soft reset to the merge-base and then recommit everything cleanly:\n\n```bash\n\n# Soft reset to the merge-base — this puts all changes in the staging area\ngit reset --soft <merge-base>\n\n# Mixed reset (unstage everything so we can restage selectively)\n# This keeps all changes in the working tree but clears the index\ngit reset HEAD\n```\n\nNow proceed as in Mode A — stage and commit changes in the planned order.\n\n**Co-Authored-By trailers:** Check recent commits on the base branch (`git log -5 <base>`)\nfor `Co-Authored-By` patterns. If the repo uses them, include the appropriate trailer on\ncommits this skill creates.\n\nAfter all commits are created, verify:\n```bash\n# The final state must be identical to the original branch tip\ngit diff HEAD $final_tree\n# This MUST produce no output. If it does, something went wrong.\n```\n\nIf the diff is not empty, something was lost or changed. Recover with `git reset --hard $final_tree` and try again.\n\n### Step 7: Handle Special Cases\n\n#### .pbxproj and Xcode Project Files\n\nXcode's `.pbxproj` file is a single file that tracks all files in an iOS/macOS project. When\nsplitting changes across commits, this file often needs to appear in multiple commits. Handle\nit carefully:\n\n- If new source files are added in different commits, each commit should include the `.pbxproj`\n  changes that reference those specific files\n- Use `git add -p` on the `.pbxproj` to stage only the relevant hunks\n- If the hunks are too interleaved to split cleanly, include the full `.pbxproj` change in the\n  first commit that needs it and note this in the commit body\n\n#### Generated Files and Lock Files\n\nFiles like `Package.resolved`, `Podfile.lock`, `yarn.lock`, `package-lock.json`:\n- Include them in the commit that changes their source (`Package.swift`, `Podfile`, etc.)\n- Don't give them their own commit unless the lock file update is the entire point\n\n#### Large Diffs\n\nIf the branch has a very large diff (50+ files, 1000+ lines), consider:\n- Reading the full diff may exceed context limits — work with `--stat` first, then read\n  individual file diffs as needed\n- Group by directory/module as a starting heuristic, then refine\n\n### Step 8: Final Verification\n\nAfter completing the commit restructuring:\n\n1. **Verify the final tree matches:**\n   - **Mode A:** Already verified in Step 6 via `git diff-tree` against `$original_tree`. No additional check needed.\n   - **Mode B:** `git diff $final_tree HEAD` — must produce no output.\n\n2. **Review the new log:**\n   ```bash\n   git log --oneline <merge-base>..HEAD\n   ```\n\n3. **Present the result to the user** — show the final commit list and confirm it looks good.\n\n4. **Show how to recover the original history:**\n   - If `backup` was used: \"Your original history is saved at `backup/<branch-name>-pre-cleanup`.\"\n   - Always: \"The original branch tip was `<sha>`. To restore: `git reset --hard <sha>`\"\n\n## Important Reminders\n\n- **Never change the final code state.** The tree at HEAD after restructuring must be identical\n  to the tree before restructuring (with the sole exception of TODO placeholders on intermediate\n  commits). If the user wants code changes, that's a separate task.\n\n- **Always record the original SHA** and show the user how to recover. Create a backup branch\n  only if `backup` is passed in ``.\n\n- **Confirm the base branch when ambiguous.** Auto-detect and proceed when there's one clear\n  candidate; only ask when multiple candidates exist or none are found.\n\n- **Show the before/after plan for history rewrites.** Even if the restructuring seems obvious,\n  the user should see what's going to change before it happens.\n\n- **Use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/).** Repo-specific\n  `CLAUDE.md` or `AGENTS.md` takes precedence if it defines its own convention.\n",
