 are reported, skip to step 4 (verify the diff).\n\n3. **Choose a resolution strategy:**\n   - **Rebase** (preferred): Use when the feature branch has clean, linear commit history.\n     ```bash\n     git rebase origin/<base-branch>\n     ```\n   - **Merge**: Use when the branch already has a non-linear history (prior merge commits).\n     ```bash\n     git merge origin/<base-branch>\n     ```\n   Resolve any conflicts, preferring the feature branch's intent while incorporating base branch additions.\n\n4. **Verify the diff after resolution.** Before pushing, compare the branch against the base to ensure only the PR's own changes are present:\n   ```bash\n   git diff origin/<base-branch>...HEAD --stat\n   ```\n   - The diff should contain **only files this PR intentionally modifies**\n   - If the diff includes many unrelated files (e.g., CODEOWNERS, marketplace.json, other plugins) this indicates a bad rebase or merge commit that pulled in unrelated changes\n   - **If the diff looks wrong:** abort immediately — `git rebase --abort` or `git reset --hard` to the pre-resolution state, then alert the user rather than pushing a polluted branch\n\n5. **Push the resolved branch:**\n   ```bash\n   git push --force-with-lease\n   ```\n\n## Phase 5: PR Creation or Update\n\n**Before creating or updating the PR**, check the conversation context for any referenced ticket IDs (e.g., `MAGE-123`, `CPRO-456`, Linear issue identifiers). If any are found:\n- Check the PR template (from Phase 1) for an existing section for ticket references (e.g., \"Related issues\", \"Tickets\", \"References\")\n- If the template has such a section, place ticket IDs there\n- If no template section exists, add a `## Related tickets` section to the PR body\n- **Use a linking phrase** so Linear's GitHub integration auto-links the issue. Choose based on intent:\n  - **Link-only** (default): `Related to MAGE-123` — also: `ref`, `references`, `part of`, `contributes to`, `towards`\n  - **Closing**: `Resolves MAGE-123` — also: `close/closes/closed/closing`, `fix/fixes/fixed/fixing`, `resolve/resolved/resolving`, `complete/completes/completed/completing`\n- Do NOT use bare ticket IDs without a phrase prefix — Linear won't detect them\n\n### Create Mode\n\n1. **Prepare PR content:**\n   - Title: Clear, concise summary of the change\n   - Body: Follow the repo's PR template exactly\n   - Include summary of changes, testing performed, related issues\n   - Include any referenced ticket IDs (see above)\n\n2. **Create the draft PR:**\n   ```bash\n   gh pr create --draft --title \"<title>\" --body \"<body>\"\n   ```\n\n3. **Report success** using the output format below.\n\n### Update Mode\n\n1. **Push new commits** if not already pushed:\n   ```bash\n   git push\n   ```\n\n2. **Evaluate the PR description:**\n   - Compare current PR body against the full branch diff and commit history\n   - Preserve manually-added context that's still relevant\n   - Rewrite from template if scope changed significantly\n\n3. **Update if needed:**\n   ```bash\n   gh pr edit <number> --body \"<updated body>\"\n   gh pr edit <number> --title \"<updated title>\"  # if title no longer fits\n   ```\n\n4. **Report success** using the output format below. Offer to start a `/pr-loop` to monitor for feedback in Github.\n\n## Important Guidelines\n\n- **Consider commit history quality** — if the branch has messy history (WIP commits, bug-then-fix sequences, scattered changes), suggest running `/clean-commit-history` before creating the PR\n- **Always create as DRAFT** — never create a non-draft PR\n- **Always ask before opening non-`rel/ci/docs` branches against `master`** — the status check will block the merge; confirm the target branch with the user first\n- **Always use the repo's template** — don't invent your own format if a template exists\n- **Read AGENTS.md first** — repo-specific instructions take precedence\n- **Be transparent about issues** — don't hide problems from the user\n- **Ask when stuck** — don't spin forever on unfixable issues\n- **Use the review playbook for thread triage** — read `review-playbook.md` from the grimoire for severity assessment, thread response, and resolution guidance\n- **Trigger BugBot:** After creating or updating a draft PR, add a comment to trigger BugBot:\n   ```bash\n   gh api repos/{owner}/{repo}/issues/{pr_number}/comments -f body=\"bugbot run\"\n   ```\n\n## Error Handling\n\n- If `gh` commands fail, check authentication: `gh auth status`\n- If the branch has no changes, report clearly and don't create an empty PR\n- If you can't determine the base branch, ask the user\n- If `gh pr view` fails in Phase 1, assume create mode\n\n## Output Format\n\n```\n## PR Created\n\n**URL:** <PR URL>\n**Status:** [Draft / Live]\n\n### Changes Made\n- Description: [Updated / No changes needed]\n- Title: [Updated / No changes needed]\n- Commits pushed: [count or \"Already up to date\"]\n\n### Review Summary\n- Iterations: X\n- Issues fixed: [list]\n- Remaining suggestions: [list or \"None\"]\n\n### Next Steps\n- Review the PR description\n- Add reviewers when ready\n- Mark as ready for review\n- Run `/pr-loop` to watch for and auto-fix review feedback\n```\n",
